<h2>Overview</h2>

<p>
  Guatemala is the world's eighth-largest coffee producer (approximately 3.7–4 million 60kg bags annually) and the most important Central American origin for specialty coffee. The country's coffee sector employs more than 250,000 farmers, over 90% of whom are smallholders farming less than one hectare. This mosaic of small farms, each working distinct microclimates and soil types, is a primary driver of Guatemalan coffee's exceptional diversity of flavor across regions.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>ANACAFE (Asociación Nacional del Café)</strong> — Guatemala's National Coffee Association — is one of the most active and effective coffee industry bodies in Central America. ANACAFE coordinates research, export promotion, farmer education, and quality standards across the entire Guatemalan coffee sector, and has been instrumental in building the country's international reputation as a premier specialty origin.
</p>

<h2>Growing Regions</h2>

<p>
  Guatemala's diverse topography — volcanoes, mountain ranges, highland plateaus, cloud forests — creates multiple geographically distinct growing regions, each with its own microclimate, soil type, and signature flavor profile.
</p>

