<h2>The Impact of Volcanic Soils</h2>

<p>
  Volcanic soil is one of Guatemala's defining agricultural assets. The country has 37 volcanoes — 3 to 4 of which are currently active — and the periodic eruptions of volcanoes like Fuego continuously replenish farmland with nutrient-rich volcanic ash.
</p>

<p>
  Key benefits of volcanic soils for coffee:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Mineral richness:</strong> Volcanic ash deposits iron, calcium, potassium, magnesium, and trace minerals into the soil with each eruption, maintaining high fertility without heavy reliance on synthetic fertilizers. This mineral abundance is believed to contribute to the distinctive cup character</li>
  <li><strong>Drainage:</strong> Porous volcanic rock and ash-rich soils drain excellently — critical for coffee root health. Good drainage prevents waterlogging while retaining adequate moisture for steady growth</li>
  <li><strong>Minerality:</strong> Many specialty coffee professionals note a distinctive mineral quality — a kind of structural complexity in the finish — as characteristic of Guatemalan cups, attributed to the unique mineral composition of the growing environment</li>
</ul>

<p>
  In Antigua specifically, Fuego volcano's periodic eruptions deposit fresh volcanic ash on surrounding farmland with some regularity. Local farmers sometimes refer to this as "natural fertilization" — a free, automatic mineral supplement that no amount of farm management can fully replicate.
</p>

<h2>Key Varieties</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Bourbon:</strong> The primary specialty variety in Guatemala. Complex flavor, good acidity. Lower yield than Caturra but capable of exceptional cup quality</li>
  <li><strong>Typica:</strong> The first variety introduced to Guatemala, historically significant. Planted area has declined but old-tree lots still produce outstanding coffee</li>
  <li><strong>Caturra:</strong> A natural dwarf mutation of Bourbon. Higher productivity. Widely planted across Guatemala</li>
  <li><strong>Catuai:</strong> The Brazilian-bred cross (Caturra × Mundo Novo). Common in Guatemala as elsewhere in Central America</li>
  <li><strong>Pache:</strong> <strong>A dwarf mutation discovered and native to Guatemala</strong> — one of the few coffee varieties that originated in Central America rather than Ethiopia or Yemen. A mutation of Typica, Pache's compact growth habit makes it easier to manage on steep terrain. An important part of Guatemala's varietal identity</li>
  <li><strong>Gesha/Geisha:</strong> Made famous by Panama, Gesha microlots from high-altitude Guatemalan farms are increasingly appearing in specialty auctions</li>
</ul>

<h2>Flavor Profile</h2>

<p>
  Guatemalan coffee's overall character can be described as <strong>full-bodied and structurally complex, with distinctive regional variation</strong>. While "chocolate" is the most consistently cited descriptor across all regions, the expression varies dramatically by origin:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Body:</strong> Full to medium-full. One of the more substantial-bodied origins in specialty coffee</li>
  <li><strong>Chocolate:</strong> The most universal characteristic. Ranges from milk chocolate and caramel (some Sul de Minas-style lots) to dark chocolate and cacao nib (Antigua), to dark cocoa powder (Cobán)</li>
  <li><strong>Dried fruit:</strong> Prune, dried cherry, raisin — particularly prominent in Antigua lots</li>
  <li><strong>Spice:</strong> Cinnamon, nutmeg, brown spice notes — especially present in Antigua and Cobán</li>
  <li><strong>Regional contrast:</strong> Huehuetenango stands apart with its bright peach, apple, and pear fruit notes and lively acidity — more similar to a good Colombian or Ethiopian washed coffee than to "typical" Guatemalan Antigua</li>
</ul>

<h2>Antigua: History and the 1976 Earthquake</h2>

<p>
  Antigua (now officially called "La Antigua Guatemala") has been a center of coffee production since the colonial era. Coffee was first cultivated in the city's monasteries and convents in the 18th century, and by the late 19th century Antigua's coffee was recognized internationally as among Central America's finest.
</p>

<p>
  The <strong>1976 earthquake</strong> (magnitude 7.5, February 4, 1976) struck Guatemala with catastrophic force — more than 23,000 people died, and highland rural communities including Antigua's coffee-growing belt were devastated. Farm infrastructure, processing facilities, and thousands of homes were destroyed. Recovery was slow and painful.
</p>

<p>
  The paradox is that reconstruction, supported by international aid and driven by farmers' determination to rebuild, ultimately modernized Antigua's coffee infrastructure. New processing facilities, improved road access, and international attention to the region's remarkable cup quality combined in the 1980s and 90s to position Antigua as one of the world's most recognized single-origin coffee designations.
</p>

<h3>SHB Grading</h3>
<p>
  Guatemala uses the <strong>SHB (Strictly Hard Bean)</strong> grading designation for coffee grown above 1,350m altitude. High altitude → cooler temperatures → slower maturation → denser bean cell structure → harder bean. This density is associated with higher sugar concentration and more complex flavor development. SHB on a Guatemalan bag is a meaningful quality signal, though it doesn't guarantee exceptional cup quality on its own.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>Guide to Choosing Guatemalan Coffee</h4>
  <p>
    <strong>By flavor goal:</strong> Classic chocolate complexity → Antigua; Bright fruit and lighter body → Huehuetenango; Rich, earthy, spicy → Cobán<br />
    <strong>Roast level:</strong> Medium to medium-dark best develops Antigua's chocolate-spice character. Huehuetenango shines at light to medium-light roast where its fruit and acidity are preserved<br />
    <strong>Brewing method:</strong> V60, Chemex, and AeroPress all work excellently. Guatemalan coffee also produces outstanding espresso shots with good structure for milk drinks<br />
    <strong>Label information to seek:</strong> Specific region (Antigua / Huehuetenango / Cobán), variety, processing method, and SHB designation — farms listing all of these are more likely to be specialty-focused<br /><br />
    Guatemala is an excellent gateway to specialty coffee for those new to single-origin exploration. Its flavors are complex enough to reward careful attention, yet familiar enough — centered on chocolate, body, and balanced sweetness — to be immediately accessible and enjoyable.
  </p>
</div>

